  },
  {
    question: "How often is interest paid on savings accounts?",
    answer: "Most high-yield savings accounts <strong>compound interest daily and pay it monthly</strong>. Daily compounding means your interest earns interest every day, maximizing your returns. With a 4.75% APY compounded daily, $10,000 grows to $10,486.38 after one year—about $11 more than with monthly compounding."
  },
  {
    question: "What's the difference between APY and interest rate?",
    answer: "<strong>APY (Annual Percentage Yield)</strong> is the true return on your money, including compound interest effects. The base interest rate doesn't account for compounding. For example, a 4.75% interest rate compounded daily yields 4.86% APY. Always compare APYs between accounts—it's the accurate measure of what you'll actually earn."
  },
  {
    question: "Can I lose money in a high-yield savings account?",
    answer: "You <strong>cannot lose your principal</strong> in an FDIC-insured savings account—your deposits are guaranteed. However, your <strong>purchasing power</strong> could decrease if inflation exceeds your interest rate. With current high-yield rates of 4-5% and inflation around 3%, you're likely gaining real purchasing power. During low-rate environments, savings may not keep pace with inflation."
  },
  {
    question: "How many savings accounts can I have?",
    answer: "There's <strong>no legal limit</strong> on savings accounts. Many savvy savers use multiple accounts strategically: one for emergency fund, one for vacation savings, one for a house down payment, etc. This 'bucket' approach helps organize goals. Some people also spread money across banks to maximize FDIC coverage ($250K limit per bank) or chase the highest rates."
  },
  {
    question: "Do I need to pay taxes on savings account interest?",
    answer: "Yes, <strong>interest earned is taxable income</strong>. Banks report interest over $10 annually to the IRS on Form 1099-INT. You'll receive this form in January and must report all interest earned on your tax return. At higher tax brackets, consider tax-advantaged options like I Bonds or municipal bond funds for some savings goals."
  },
  {
    question: "What happens to savings rates when the Fed cuts rates?",
    answer: "High-yield savings rates typically <strong>decline when the Federal Reserve cuts rates</strong>, though not immediately or proportionally. Banks adjust gradually. After the Fed's 2024 rate cuts, top savings rates fell from 5.5% to 4.5-5%. If you want to lock in current rates, consider <strong>certificates of deposit (CDs)</strong> which guarantee your rate for the term length."
  },
